Ricotti, Gnedin, + Shull, 2002
OTVET for cosmological galaxy formation, H2 LyWerner. Chemistry for H2 formation/destruction, molecular + atomic cooling, ionization by secondary electrons, and heating by Ly Alpha scattering. "We find that the first galaxies (``small-halo galaxies'') are characterized by bursting star formation, self-regulated by a feedback process that acts on cosmological scales. The mass in stars produced by these objects can exceed the mass in stars produced by normal galaxies; therefore, their impact on cosmic evolution cannot be neglected." More results in companion paper.
@ARTICLE{2002ApJ...575...33R,
   author = {{Ricotti}, M. and {Gnedin}, N.~Y. and {Shull}, J.~M.},
    title = "{The Fate of the First Galaxies. I. Self-consistent Cosmological Simulations with Radiative Transfer}",
